## Template and Manifest Generators

Add these as module-level functions in `extension-manager.ts` (or a separate `extension-templates.ts` if the file gets large):

```typescript
/** Convert kebab-case to PascalCase: "github-prs" -> "GithubPrs" */
function toPascalCase(str: string): string {
  return str
    .split('-')
    .map((s) => s.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + s.slice(1))
    .join('');
}

/** Convert kebab-case to Title Case: "github-prs" -> "Github Prs" */
function toTitleCase(str: string): string {
  return str
    .split('-')
    .map((s) => s.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + s.slice(1))
    .join(' ');
}

/** Generate the extension.json manifest content. */
function generateManifest(
  name: string,
  description?: string,
  template?: string
): object {
  const contributions: Record<string, boolean> = {};
  switch (template) {
    case 'dashboard-card':
      contributions['dashboard.sections'] = true;
      break;
    case 'command':
      contributions['command-palette.items'] = true;
      break;
    case 'settings-panel':
      contributions['settings.tabs'] = true;
      break;
  }

  return {
    id: name,
    name: toTitleCase(name),
    version: '0.1.0',
    ...(description && { description }),
    author: 'agent',
    minHostVersion: '0.1.0',
    contributions,
  };
}

/** Select and generate the index.ts template content. */
function generateTemplate(
  name: string,
  description: string,
  template: 'dashboard-card' | 'command' | 'settings-panel'
): string {
  switch (template) {
    case 'dashboard-card':
      return generateDashboardCardTemplate(name, description);
    case 'command':
      return generateCommandTemplate(name, description);
    case 'settings-panel':
      return generateSettingsPanelTemplate(name, description);
  }
}
```

The three template generators produce the exact code shown in the specification sections 5.2, 5.3, and 5.4. Each template includes:

- A header comment block with the extension name, description, and a compact API Quick Reference listing the most commonly used methods and all available slot names
- An import of `ExtensionAPI` type from `@dorkos/extension-api`
- A component function (for dashboard-card and settings-panel) or just registration code (for command)
- An `activate(api)` function that registers the contribution in the appropriate slot

### `dashboard-card` template (default):

Produces a React component `{PascalCaseName}Section` with inline styles (padding, border, border-radius) and an `activate()` function that calls `api.registerComponent('dashboard.sections', '{name}-section', Component, { priority: 50 })`.

### `command` template:

Produces an `activate()` function that calls `api.registerCommand('{name}-run', '{Title Case Name}', callback, { icon: 'terminal' })` where the callback calls `api.notify('{Title Case Name} executed!', { type: 'success' })`.

### `settings-panel` template:

Produces a React component `{PascalCaseName}Settings` with a heading and description, and an `activate()` function that calls `api.registerSettingsTab('{name}-settings', '{Title Case Name}', Component)`.

## Error Handling

- If directory already exists: throw `new Error(\`Extension '${name}' already exists at ${targetDir}\`)`
- If scope is local with no CWD: throw `new Error('Cannot create local extension: no working directory is active')`
- If filesystem write fails: propagate the OS error (caller handles)
- If compilation fails after scaffolding: return the result with `status: 'compile_error'` and error details â€” the files remain on disk for the agent to fix

## Acceptance Criteria

- `createExtension()` creates the directory, `extension.json`, and `index.ts` on disk
- Three templates produce valid TypeScript that compiles with esbuild
- Local scope uses `{currentCwd}/.dork/extensions/{name}/`
- Global scope uses `{dorkHome}/extensions/{name}/`
- Throws descriptive error when directory already exists
- Throws descriptive error when local scope requested with no CWD
- After creation, the extension is discovered, compiled, and added to the enabled list
- Generated manifest includes correct `contributions` for the template type
- `pnpm typecheck` passes

